iven the length. Looking at the maskingPatterns section more carefully, the knowledge file captures the essential mechanism even though it leaves out the concrete example of `<password>hoge</password>` becoming `<password>****</password>`. Since the core logic is still clear, this is a minor gap rather than a critical omission.\n\nLet me recount the RST heading structure to verify the section count issue—the title uses a lower-level marker, and there are four main sections below it, which explains why the automated check flagged it as having fewer sections than expected. Overall, the knowledge file appears sound with only these minor structural quirks. The structure actually makes sense—the five h2 sections form a cohesive overview while the four h3 sections provide detailed reference material, so this isn't a real issue. Looking back at the evaluation criteria, I should only report findings where the source file actually justifies a problem, and here the organization is intentional and logical, so I won't flag this as a finding. I'm settling on flagging this as a minor section_issue—the knowledge file consolidates five distinct source sections into a single s1, which makes it substantially larger than the four format subsections in s2-s5, and this could impact how efficiently the AI retrieves specific information. Let me finalize my findings and verify the hex dump data in the output example to make sure everything checks out. I'm examining the knowledge file structure and noticing a discrepancy in the section count—the automated warning flags 5 sections against 6 source headings, which suggests the document title is being counted separately from the h2 headings. This is a minor structural issue but worth noting since knowledge files have a dedicated title field that shouldn't be counted as a heading. I need to check the character counts for each h2 section individually to see if any exceed 2000 characters, since that's the threshold for the V3 validation rule. Looking at the estimates, sections 4 and 5 likely cross that threshold, but section 4 already has h3 subsections that are properly split, so it wouldn't trigger the warning. The real issue is that all 5 h2 sections are being merged into a single s1 section, which is why the automated system flagged it as a minor structural concern.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":25914,"cache_read_input_tokens":18561,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":25914,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":8},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fd7e6b02-0579-45c9-9ebe-e5b0cbd70042","uuid":"0c4019c8-3041-4005-901c-25fbb0d047b3"}
